<p style="text-align:right;"><strong><em>Annexure I</em></strong></p>
<p><strong>DESCRIPTION OF TERMS (PEOPLE MANAGEMENT, GOOD GOVERNANCE AND CONTROL AND CUSTOMER CARE CATEGORY). </strong></p>
<P><strong>A. People Management </strong></P>
<P><strong>a) Employee Productivity Rate </strong></P>
<p>Total revenue divided by the total number of employees. (May consider own source revenue divided by the number of staff directly related with generation of this source).</p>

<p><strong>b) Employee Satisfaction Rate; </strong>this indicator is derived from the annual employee satisfaction survey conducted by the specific organization. The survey can measure both overall satisfaction level and satisfaction with different facets of the job and organization. The parameter of interest shall be the overall satisfaction level measured by the percentage of employee extremely satisfied with their jobs (depending on the measurement scale).</p>

<p><strong>c) Average Training Hours Per employee</strong> - Training Hours per Employee measures the number of hours existing employees (does not include new employees) spend in training compared to the number of employees undergoing training over the same period. The formula for measuring average training hours per employee is Total Number of Hours Existing Employees Spend Training / Number of Employees Undergoing Training. Key issues to consider when calculating average training hours per employee include;
</p>
<ol>
<li>Do not include new employees in this calculation</li>
<li>Training is considered as time spent by employees in formal programs (can consist of online modules and physical attendances directly related sharpening the employee skills</li>
<li>Do not include informal training sessions, i.e., time spent outside of formally recognized training programs or time taken by an employee who independently trains themselves.</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>d) % of Employees participating in Training</strong> – this is calculated by the total number of employees trained / number of trainable employee’s x 100</p>
<p><strong>e) Percentage of employees receiving regular performance feedback </strong>– this is calculated by the total number of employees receiving performance feedback / the total number of employees in an organization eligible for receiving performance feedback;</p>
